04312nam a22006615i 9781487512163DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20192019onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875121637 a10.3138/97814875121632doi  a(DE-B1597)525916  a(OCoLC)1080190638  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aHF1019 7aBUS0470002bisacsh1 aGunia, Brian , eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Bartering Mindset :bA Mostly Forgotten Framework for Mastering Your Next Negotiation /cBrian Gunia. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (248 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. The Limits of the Monetary Mindset -- t2. The Bartering Mindset -- t3. Step 1: Deeply and Broadly Define Your Needs and Offerings -- t4. Steps 2–3: Map Out the Full Range of Transaction Partners and the Full Range of Their Possible Needs and Offerings -- t5. Step 4: Anticipate the Most Powerful Set of Partnerships across the Market -- t6. Step 5: Cultivate the Most Powerful Set of Partnerships across the Market -- t7. Integrating the Bartering and Monetary Mindsets -- t8. Objections to the Bartering Mindset -- t9. Conclusions and Applications -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWe use money to solve our everyday problems, and it generally works well. Despite its economic benefits, however, money has a psychological downside: it trains us to think about negotiations narrow-mindedly, leading us to negotiate badly. Suggesting that we need a non-monetary mindset to negotiate better, The Bartering Mindset shows us how to look outside the monetary economy – to the bartering economies of the past, where people traded what they had for what they needed. The book argues that, because of the economic difficulties associated with bartering, barterers had to use a more sophisticated form of negotiation – a strategic approach that can make us master negotiators today. This book immerses readers in the assumptions made by barterers, collectively referred to as the "bartering mindset," and then demonstrates how to apply this mindset to modern, monetary negotiations. The Bartering Mindset concludes that our individual, organizational, and social problems fester for a predictable reason: we apply a monetary mindset to our negotiations, leading to suboptimal thinking, counterproductive behaviors, and disappointing outcomes. By offering the bartering mindset as an alternative, this book will help people negotiate better and thrive.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aBarter. 0aNegotiationxEconomic aspects. 4aDISCOUNT-C. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Negotiating.2bisacsh  aanalysis.  abartering mindset.  abartering.  aconflict management.  adecision-making.  ahistory of bartering.  ahistory of negotiation.  aintegrative negotiation.  amonetary mindset.  amoney.  anegotiation.  aproblem-solving.  astakeholder.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065206240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148751216340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487512163423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487512163.jpg  a978-3-11-065206-2  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles